hands_on_practices.problem:
According to the Fundamental Theorem of Finite Abelian Groups, any finite abelian group is isomorphic to a direct product of cyclic groups whose orders are prime powers. These prime-power orders are known as the elementary divisors of the group. A complete set of elementary divisors, disregarding their order, uniquely determines the group up to isomorphism.

Consider the following sets of integers. Which one of these sets CANNOT represent the collection of elementary divisors for any finite abelian group?

A. {4, 9, 25}

B. {8, 3, 3, 5}

C. {2, 2, 2, 9, 5}

D. {4, 6, 25}

E. {4, 2, 5, 5}

Let $G$ be a finite abelian group that is also a $p$-group for the prime $p=3$. The group's structure is unknown, but the following properties have been determined:
(i) The number of elements of order 3 is exactly 242.
(ii) The number of elements of order 9 is exactly 19440.
(iii) The number of elements of order 27 is exactly 157464.
(iv) The number of elements of order 81 is exactly 354294.
(v) There are no elements with an order greater than 81.

Based on this information, which of the following represents the multiset of elementary divisors of $G$?

A. {3, 9, 9, 27, 81}

B. {3, 9, 9, 81, 81}

C. {3, 27, 27, 27, 27}

D. {3, 9, 27, 81, 81}

E. {9, 9, 9, 9, 9}
